{{no footnotes|date=February 2018}} [[File:Carolina Ferni.jpg|thumb|Carolina Ferni]]
'''Carolina Ferni''' (20 August 1846 &ndash; 4 June 1926) was an Italian [[violin]]ist and operatic [[soprano]].
Ferni was born in [[Como]]. She began her career as a violinist in [[Paris]] and [[Brussels]], and later studied voice with famed soprano [[Giuditta Pasta]]. She made her stage debut in [[Turin]] in 1862 as Leonora in [[Donizetti]]'s ''[[La favorite]]''. She sang at [[La Scala]] in Milan (1866–68) as [[Norma (opera)|Norma]], [[L'Africaine|Selika]] and [[Saffo (opera)|Saffo]], among other roles. In [[Agostino Mercuri]]'s opera ''Il Violino del Diavolo'', she both sang and played the violin.
She was married to the prominent [[Verdi]] baritone [[Leone Giraldoni]] (1824–1897). They had a son, [[Eugenio Giraldoni]], whom she taught. Like his father, Eugenio became an operatic baritone, creating the role of Scarpia in [[Puccini]]'s ''[[Tosca]]'' in 1900.
Ferni retired from the stage in 1883, and opened a singing school in Milan, and later in [[St. Petersburg]], Russia. Among her students was the soprano [[Eugenia Burzio]]. She died in [[Milan]] in 1926, two years after her son.
==Sources==
