'''Kalikrishna Mitra''' ( 1822 - 2 August 1891) was a [[Bengalis|Bengali]] philanthropist, educator and writer. He established the first non-government girls’ school in [[India]].<ref name=":0" /> ==Early life== Mitra was born to Shibnarayan Mitra in [[Kolkata]], [[British India]]. He passed from [[Hare School]] and entered into the [[Presidency College Calcutta|Presidency College]] but due to poor economic condition he had to left study and started living in his maternal house at [[Barasat]] (presently [[North 24 Parganas district]]). His elder brother was a notable doctor, Nabinkrishna Mitra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Isvar_Chandra_Vidyasagar,_a_story_of_his_life_and_work/Chapter_15|title=Isvar Chandra Vidyasagar, a story of his life and work|last=Chapter 15|first=Subal Chandra Mitra|date=|website=en.wikisource.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=April 21, 2018}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> ==Contribution== Mitra involved with progressive education movement and several social reformative actions in [[Bengal]]. In 1847 he established a private girls school in Barasat with the help of his brother Nabinkrishna and educationist [[Peary Charan Sarkar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bgc.org.in/history.php|title=Barasat Government College|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=April 21, 2018}}</ref> This was the first school for the girls of aristocratic [[Hindu]] families established by any Indian.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.socialresearchfoundation.com/upoadreserchpapers/5/190/1802061145301st%20chiranjit%20roy.pdf|title=Madanmohan Tarkalankar and Women Education in the First Half of 19th Century Bengal|last=Chiranjit Roy|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=April 21, 2018}}</ref> Initially it was started with only two girls. ''Kuntibala'', daughter of Nabinkrishna is one of them. Although such activities was strongly opposed by Hindu [[Zamindar|Zaminders]] and the then conservative society but [[Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar]] and [[John Elliot Drinkwater Bethune]] supported Mitra's enormous effort for women education in Bengal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=91xAzuqbha0C&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&dq=kalikrishna+mitra&source=bl&ots=PcZwg13RuJ&sig=i_OGCt78h9Ke0-JXkRIhNeLRY90&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiAi_CM8sraAhXKPY8KHT9gBTA4ChDoAQgpMAE#v=onepage&q=kalikrishna%20mitra&f=false|title=Hindu Widow Marriage|last=Ishvarchandra Vidyasagar|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=April 21, 2018}}</ref> Latter the school was renamed as [[Kalikrishna Girls' High School]]. Even Bethune got inspiration for establishment Bethune School in 1949, when he went there for inspection as President of the Council of Education.<ref>Bagal, Jogesh C., ''History of The Bethune School and College'' in the ''Bethune School and College Centenary Volume, 1849–1949. ''</ref> Mitra organised an agricultural firm of 150 ''Bighas'' for scientific farming, plantation and research in Barasat. He brought modern equipment from [[England]] for this purpose. He also contributed to spread out for [[Homeopathy]] medication.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=Sansad Bangali Charitabhidhan|last=Vol II|first=Anjali Basu|publisher=Sahitya Sansad|year=2004|isbn=81-86806-99-7|location=Kolkata|pages=78}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=q4k9ILvAcE4C&pg=PA87&lpg=PA87&dq=kalikrishna+mitra&source=bl&ots=BDynOWxBNt&sig=j_VDn2z4dtk8Jdun76ZposK3QZk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiAi_CM8sraAhXKPY8KHT9gBTA4ChDoAQgsMAI#v=onepage&q=kalikrishna%20mitra&f=false|title=Nationalizing the Body: The Medical Market, Print and Daktari Medicine|last=Projit Bihari Mukharji|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=April 21, 2018}}</ref>
==Literary works== Mitra had knowledge in English literature, philosophy, yoga, history and science. He published various articles in Bengali and English magazines. Mitra wrote few books namely<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.338641|title=Garhasthya-byabastha O Shishu Chikitsa|last=Mitra, Kalikrishna|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=April 21, 2018}}</ref>: * ''Bama Chikitsa'' * ''Garhasthyobabostha O Shishu Chikitsa'' * ''Pashu Chikitsa'' ==References== {{Reflist}}
